    <h2>Social Media Image Size Guide 2026</h2>
    <p>Getting the right image dimensions for social media is critical for making your content look polished and professional. Each platform has specific requirements for profile pictures, cover photos, feed posts, stories, and ads. Using the wrong size can result in awkward cropping, blurry images, or wasted ad spend.</p>

    <h2>Why Image Dimensions Matter</h2>
    <p>Social media algorithms prioritize content that looks native to the platform. Images that are the correct size load faster, display without cropping artifacts, and signal to the algorithm that your content is high-quality. This directly impacts reach and engagement.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Avoid cropping:</strong> Platforms auto-crop images to fit their layout. Using the correct dimensions ensures your subject stays in frame.</li>
      <li><strong>Faster loading:</strong> Oversized images are compressed server-side, which can introduce artifacts. Right-sized images stay sharp.</li>
      <li><strong>Ad compliance:</strong> Platforms reject ads that don't meet their dimension requirements, wasting setup time.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Universal Sizes That Work Cross-Platform</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>1080 x 1080 (1:1):</strong> Works on Instagram, Facebook, LinkedIn, and Pinterest feed posts.</li>
      <li><strong>1080 x 1920 (9:16):</strong> The standard for Stories and Reels across Instagram, Facebook, TikTok, YouTube Shorts, Snapchat, and Pinterest.</li>
      <li><strong>1200 x 630 (1.91:1):</strong> The standard for shared link previews on Facebook, Twitter/X, LinkedIn, Discord, and Slack.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Tips for Resizing Images</h2>
    <p>Use the dimension checker above to see which platforms your current image fits. When resizing, always maintain the aspect ratio to avoid stretching. For best results, design at the target dimensions rather than scaling down from a larger image. Save as PNG for graphics with text, and JPEG for photographs at 80-90% quality.</p>
